  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Media Training Transitnal Justice Gambia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The establishment of the Truth, Reconciliations and Reparation Commission; and The Gambia&#x2019;s reversal of its decision to with-draw from the Rome Statute for the International Criminal Court provide an opportunity for Gambian media to contribute to the development and protection of democracy and its institutions in the Gambia, by contributing to public discourses on addressing the legacy of massive and systematic human rights violations. The purpose of the training is to build the capacity of the media in Gambia to effectively report on and generate constructive public debates on international criminal justice and transitional justice developments at the local, national, regional and inter-national levels. The media&#x2019;s engagement in generating constructive public debates on accountability will in turn ensure that the media is strategically placed to advance the democratization process in The Gambia. Ultimately, the trainings will promote a victim focused approach and inculcate a culture of responsible and analytical reporting among Gambian journalists on issues relating to international criminal justice ad transitional justice, enabling them to disseminate relevant, factual, and credible information on accountability processes. The specific objectives of the training are to: &#x2022; Educate and enhance knowledge of select media professionals on ICJ and transitional justice mechanisms, challenges, and opportunities in the Gambia; &#x2022; Strengthen the technical capacity of journalists to document in a professional and interactive manner, (including basic understanding of legal trials, observation of trials, balanced reporting, journalism ethics, and the attitude of journalists towards victims); &#x2022; Facilitate the contact and exchange with the ICC on the court in general and sharing of the institution&#x2019;s experience with  crimes against humanity/mass atrocity crimes ; &#x2022; Generate public debates on ICJ/TJ using various media platforms; &#x2022; Facilitate best practices, lessons learned and experience sharing between Gambian media professionals and media professionals from Liberia, and Kenya .</narrative>
  </description>
